    "Id": "456373",
    "ThreadId": "216281",
    "Html": "<p>Hi,</p>\r\n<p>Typically in this case you would trigger whatever calculation you are doing in the SelectedPerson property. Use something like this:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n<div style=\"color:black;background-color:white\">\r\n<pre><span style=\"color:blue\">public</span> <span style=\"color:blue\">const</span> <span style=\"color:blue\">string</span> SelectedPersonPropertyName = <span style=\"color:#a31515\">&quot;SelectedPerson&quot;</span>;\r\n<span style=\"color:blue\">private</span> Person _person = <span style=\"color:blue\">null</span>;\r\n<span style=\"color:blue\">public</span> Person SelectedPerson\r\n{\r\n    <span style=\"color:blue\">get</span>\r\n    {\r\n        <span style=\"color:blue\">return</span> _person;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    <span style=\"color:blue\">set</span>\r\n    {\r\n        <span style=\"color:blue\">if</span> (_person == value)\r\n        {\r\n            <span style=\"color:blue\">return</span>;\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        _person = value;\r\n        RaisePropertyChanged(SelectedPersonPropertyName);\r\n        HandlePersonChanged(_person);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n</div>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>To answer your question, I am not aware of a way to control the order in which the events, triggers and bindings are fired.</p>\r\n<p>Cheers,</p>\r\n<p>Laurent</p>",
    "PostedDate": "2010-06-16T14:24:32.51-07:00",
    "UserRole": null,
    "MarkedAsAnswerDate": null
  },
